    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Certainly, let's dive into the math without the goblin shenanigans this time. If you have a student loan with a balance of $10,000 and an annual interest rate of 5%, the interest for the year would be calculated as follows:\n\nInterest for the year = Principal balance x Interest rate\nInterest for the year = $10,000 x 0.05 = $500\n\nNow, if you're making monthly payments, the interest for each month would be a portion of that $500. For simplicity, let's say you're making equal monthly payments that cover the interest and a portion of the principal. The interest for each month would be:\n\nMonthly interest = Annual interest / 12\nMonthly interest = $500 / 12 ≈ $41.67\n\nSo, each month, about $41.67 of your payment goes towards interest. The rest goes towards reducing the principal. If your monthly payment is, say, $100, then $41.67 goes to interest and $58.33 goes to the principal.\n\nNow, why does it feel like the interest is eating your payments? Because the interest is calculated on the remaining balance, which decreases as you make payments. So, in the beginning, when your balance is",
